title: For Sale:  Rem 700 Custon Benchrest .223, Floated Lilja Match 1:8 Barrel, 1.5 oz Jewel Trigger, Sight Mark Scope, Bell and Carlson Stock, PTG Custom Fluted Bolt, Accu-shot monopod and Harris Bipod
postcontent: Up for sale is my favorite rifle. It is being sold because of a bad financial situation only! If I had my choice I would keep this for life. Over $3400 invested in this gun and it shoots better than it looks. This is a Remington 700 rebuilt to be a competition bench-rest rifle. It has a 1.5 oz (up to 3lbs) jewel trigger, custom fully floated Teflon coated Lilja 1:8 twist match grade heavy barrel, Bell and Carlson stock, PTG custom bolt matched and trued to the gun. The gun includes an Accu-shot monopod and a Harris Bipod when not being used as a benchrest gun. It also has a Sight Mark 10-40x56mm scope which is impressive for what it is. This gun shoots 1/4 MOA easy and probably better with a better operator. I bought this gun, rebuilt it over a winter, broke in the barrel and built the loads in the spring, once I found the best load I put it in the case where it's been for 3 years. This gun looks and is brand new minus the break in procedure. It will shoot normal .223 ammo at 1/2 MOA all day, but shoots better with longer 77-80gr custom loads. This is the last thing in the world I want to sell, but my financial situation doesn't give me any other option. There is over $3400 worth of labor and parts put into this gun and it can be yours for far less. I am asking $2300 or best reasonable offer. I also have competition reloading equipment for sale as well. Please email me with any questions. The gun will be in a shop on consignment until it is sold, so if you want to check it out shoot me an email and I will let you know where you can go to check it out.

postcontent:
This is an at least very hard to find, if not very rare gun, especially since itâ€™s for sale.  I am the second owner, the first claimed to have never shot it, and I never have myself. It is essentially new in the original box, with all accessories (sling, cleaning kit, oil bottle, bayonet, etc), including three 30 round magazines that are still in the cosmoline stained bags.  It probably goes without saying, but this is an original all numbers matching gun; the receiver, the receiver cover, the bolt carrier, the bolt, and the trigger guard. The only exception is the stock which is unmarked, likely because the SKS-D was never issued as a military weapon and the stock had to be specially made for this civilian D model. Some of these rifles came with matching serial numbered magazines, but I canâ€™t tell through the bags and Iâ€™m not going  to open them to check.

This is a very early edition (probably mid 70â€™s Iâ€™m told), imported from Norinco by CSI in Dallas, Texas (God Bless Texas!) It is definitely NOT one of the later and much more common â€œsporterizedâ€ models; the ones with the metal glob where the bayonet  used to go and those awful thumbhole stocks,  most of which look and feel like they  were hacked out of a old plank by a chimpanzee.  In addition to the intact bayonet lug and nice stock (with cleaning kit storage), early models had screw in barrels instead of pinned, this has the stripper guide bolt carrier, the AK style â€œbutterflyâ€ mag release, the steel-lined magwell,  and this not only still has itâ€™s bayonet, it is the correct SKS-D tooless removeable type (the bayonet is rare all by itself).

I had the guys at Ron Petersonâ€™s take a look at this gun and I was told that for insurance or a collector "it should be worth well over a thousand dollars, maybe up to $1500â€. I am only selling because I have two and  Iâ€™ll never take this one out of the box to shoot it. title: For Sale:  Berkshire Arms Valtro 1998 A1 .45 ACP Custom 1911
postcontent:
The 1998A1 .45 ACP pistol is patterned after the legendary Colt 1911A1. The 1998A1 is a 'near custom' production handgun that has as standard features the "extras" that only custom makers put on their pistols. The 1998A1 is a gorgeous piece of work which is not only pleasing to the eyes and hands but supremely accurate, durable, and is a tightly machined example of the highest quality production firearms.

The 1998A1 is the product of many years of work by Master Pistolsmith John Jardine of Jardine's Custom. His vision was to create a handgun of the finest materials that would have the performance, look and feel of a custom gun right out of the box.

Mr. Jardine's design has been an ongoing project which has taken years to accomplish. During John's long career as a pistolsmith he made note of each item, part, or procedure that he found to be beneficial to a 1911 style handgun. As the years passed he added these new procedures or design ideas to his 'ultimate' design and eventually he was ready to mass produce his dream pistol and began to look for a suitable manufacturer.

During the course of his normal business John had been contracted by Valtro Stocchetta of Italy as a consultant helping them to improve the quality and reliability of their firearms. One thing led to another and a deal was struck for Valtro to produce the pistol Jardine had always dreamed of making. Mr. Jardine retained control of the manufacturing process making numerous trips to Italy checking on the materials, tolerances, quality control issues, and manufacturing practices in detail.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1936 Pre-WWII Luger 9mm
location: Tulsa and Surrounding Areas, Tulsa, Oklahoma
postcontent:
This is a very scarce early Pre-WWII German Luger manufactured by the Mauser factory. This was the first year that Germany stopped using the secret letter code markings for the year of manufacture on small arms. The chamber area is stamped "1936" and the front toggle is marked "S/42", the wartime code for the Mauser factory. The right side of the barrel extension has the early double "Eagle/63" Waffenamt proofs. It is numbered in the military fashion with the full serial number stamped on the major components and the last two digits on the various small parts. The grips are checkered walnut.
Excellent overall with 95% of the original blue finish with wear on the edges and high spots overall with blue loss on the side plate, muzzle area front frame rails with a hint of thinning on the lower grips strap. The straw colors are vivid and remain 80% intact. The grips are excellent with nice original distinct checkering on both sides, mixed with some minor handling marks. This Luger has all matching upper serial numbers and all matching lower serial numbers as is normal for a Mauser produced luger made in 1936 and referenced in the information noted in the Gun Digest article below.

The Luger Pistol
From Gun Digest Book, 11th Edition, 1957.
By: Fred A. Datig | April 20, 2009
The 1936 was the last year that Mauser used the traditional straw bluing on the small parts. Wartime production was starting up and demand required that the trigger, thumb safety, locking lever magazine release were converted to salt bluing in early 1937. Pre WWII manufacture means it was made as good as they ever were.
Beginning in 1936 Krieghoff, like Mauser, dated his products with the year of manufacture in numbers. A few examples may be encountered bearing dates of â€œ1936â€³ and â€œ1937â€³ which do not conform to the proper serial number range. These were pieces assembled from already numbered surplus parts at those later dates. These will have the 1936 S/42 upper all matching and all lower all matching. Some of the Mauser-made Lugers will be found bearing not only the commercial Mauser Banner but also carrying a date-stamp over the chamber. Such arms were originally intended for commercial sale, but when the German military forces demanded more Lugers than normal Mauser production could supply, pistols previously set aside for the commercial market were merely stamped with a date and accepted by the Army as regular issue weapons. In 1936 the secret code names were augmented. Mauser was assigned the code number â€œ42â€³ in addition to the â€œS/42â€³ already in use.

It is not unusual, then, to find Lugers bearing the code name â€œS/42â€³ and, for example, the date â€œ1936,â€ and also to encounter â€œ42â€³ pieces having the same date. To add to the confusion, pieces were also produced bearing the same date, â€œ1936,â€ and inscribed with the commercial Mauser Banner.
The Luger Pistol
From Gun Digest Book, 11th Edition, 1957.
By: Fred A. Datig | April 20, 2009
Editorâ€™s Note: This is a sample article from Gun Digest Research, where you can search thousands of archived Gun Digest Annual Book archives. To learn more go to http://research.gundigest.com.
